This paper was presented as part of the main technical program at IEEE INFOCOM 2011

SOAP: A Social Network Aided Personalized and Effective Spam Filter to Clean Your E-mail Box
Ze Li and Haiying Shen Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering
Clemson University Clemson, SC 29631 Email: {zel, shenh}@clemson.edu

Abstract‚ÄîThe explosive growth of unsolicited emails has prompted the development of numerous spam Ô¨Åltering techniques. A Bayesian spam Ô¨Ålter is superior to a static keywordbased spam Ô¨Ålter because it can continuously evolve to tackle new spam by learning keywords in new spam emails. However, Bayesian spam Ô¨Ålters can be easily poisoned by avoiding spam keywords and adding many innocuous keywords in the emails. In addition, they need a signiÔ¨Åcant amount of time to adapt to a new spam based on user feedback. Moreover, few current spam Ô¨Ålters exploit social networks to assist spam detection. In order to develop an accurate and user-friendly spam Ô¨Ålter, in this paper, we propose a SOcial network Aided Personalized and effective spam Ô¨Ålter (SOAP). Unlike previous Ô¨Ålters that focus on parsing keywords (e.g, Bayesian Ô¨Ålter) or building blacklists, SOAP exploits the social relationship among email correspondents to detect the spam adaptively and automatically. SOAP integrates three components into the basic Bayesian Ô¨Ålter: social closeness-based spam Ô¨Åltering, social interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering, and adaptive trust management. We evaluate performance of SOAP based on the trace data from Facebook. Experimental results show that SOAP can greatly improve the performance of Bayesian spam Ô¨Ålters in terms of the accuracy, attack-resilience and efÔ¨Åciency of spam detection. We also Ô¨Ånd that the performance of Bayesian spam Ô¨Ålters is the lower bound of SOAP.
I. INTRODUCTION
Internet email is one of the most popular communication methods in the realm of our business and daily lives. Internet email has been reliable throughout most of its long history. However, spam is becoming the penultimate problem in email systems, accelerating at an alarming speed. Unsolicited commercial emails have increased from approximately 10% of overall email volume in 1998 to as much as 80% today [1]. Currently, 120 billion spam emails are sent per day [2], with a projected cost of $338 billion by 2013 [3]. Spam emails interfere with both email service providers and end users. It forces users to search legitimate (i.e., non-spam) emails in an inbox Ô¨Ålled with spam. Spam emails also take up a huge amount of bandwidth that otherwise could be used to transmit more useful information.
The fundamental way to prevent spam is to make it unproÔ¨Åtable to send spam emails and thereby destroying the spammers‚Äô underlying business model [4]. Oscar et. al. indicated that there is a strong relationship between the average cost of sending spam, spam detection accuracy and spam Ô¨Ålter deployment [4]. SpeciÔ¨Åcally, any measure that stops spam from reaching users‚Äô inboxes with probability p and is

deployed by users with probability q increases the average cost of sending spam by 1/(1 ‚àí pq). This means that in order to increase the cost, a spam Ô¨Ålter should increase detection accuracy p and user deployment q. Such a spam Ô¨Ålter should be attack-resilient, personalized and user-friendly.
The attack-resilient and personalized features are important to achieve higher accuracy. A higher accurate Ô¨Ålter generates less false positives and false negatives. False positives are the legitimate emails that are mistakenly regarded as spam emails. False negatives are the spam emails that are not detected. There are primarily two types of spam Ô¨Ålter attacks: poison attack and impersonation attack. In a poison attack, many legitimate keywords are added to a spam email, thus decreasing its probability of being detected as spam. In an impersonation attack, a spammer impersonates the identities of ordinary users by forging their IDs or compromising their computers. An estimated 50% - 80% of all spam worldwide was sent by compromised computers, also known as zombies [5], in the year of 2005. An attack-resilient spam Ô¨Ålter can detect spam emails in these attacks.
By personalized, we mean that an accurate spam Ô¨Ålter should consider the social situation of a particular individual in detecting spam. First, it considers social closeness between correspondents. Closer social relationship between two persons implies high trust between them [6]. People treat emails sent by strangers and acquaintances differently. Emails containing keywords such as ‚Äúlose weight‚Äù are usually regarded as spam. However, such keywords may be in the emails sent between members of a health club. Commercial emails are usually considered as spam. However, the email sender may be the receiver‚Äôs friend and believes the advertisement-like information beneÔ¨Åts the receiver. Second, a spam Ô¨Ålter considers different (dis)interests of individuals. For example, an email about ‚Äúfootball‚Äù is not spam to football fans, but is spam to those who are not interested in football. Thus, determining a legitimate mail is different from person to person. A userfriendly (i.e., easy-to-use) spam Ô¨Ålter does not require a large amount of manual spam detection activities from users.
However, few previous spam Ô¨Åltering approaches can meet the requirements of being user-friendly, attack-resilient and personalized. We list the main approaches in Table I with their features. Most approaches do not take into account the different closeness relationship and (dis)interests of individu-

978-1-4244-9921-2/11/$26.00 ¬©2011 IEEE 1835

als. They usually consider unsolicited commercial emails and investment request emails as spam. This traditional view of spam is not sufÔ¨Åciently accurate.
Previous spam Ô¨Ålter approaches can be mainly divided into two categories: content-based and identity-based. In the content-based category, emails are parsed and scored based on the keywords and patterns which are typical in spam. The simplest spam Ô¨Ålter is static keyword-based Ô¨Ålter [7], in which a spam keyword blacklist is built. However, it cannot adapt to the continuously changing characteristics of spam. Machine learning approaches [8]‚Äì[15] can adaptively learn new spam keywords. In these approaches, the spam Ô¨Ålters are trained with a corpus of both spam and legitimate emails. Characteristics of the spam and legitimate emails are identiÔ¨Åed respectively. The characteristics are used to automatically categorize future emails into the two classes. However, machine learning approaches still suffer from a number of problems. First, in order to increase the efÔ¨Åciency and accuracy of training, the spam Ô¨Ålters are normally installed in an email server to collect all the training samples. Thus, they are not personalized. Second, the spam Ô¨Ålters are vulnerable to poison attacks. Third, the spam Ô¨Ålters are not user-friendly. They require a lot of user efforts to manually distinguish the spam from legitimate emails for training.

