efforts contribute to the high accuracy of SOAP. The social closeness-based spam Ô¨Åltering component checks emails based on the closeness between the receiver and the sender. A smaller closeness value leads to more strict checking, while a larger closeness value leads to loose checking. Since the emails sent between people with close relationship normally has low probability to be spam, the spam detection accuracy rate can be increased. The interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering component increases the spam detection accuracy by Ô¨Åltering out the emails in the receiver‚Äôs disinterests and accepts the emails that match the receiver‚Äôs interests. The experimental results imply that the values of œÅI and œÅD in the interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering component need to be equal and large.
Figure 5 demonstrates the accuracy rate of SOAP and Bayesian with different training sample sizes. It shows that SOAP always produces a higher accuracy rate than Bayesian, and the accuracy rate of Bayesian increases as the sample size grows. SOAP has less dependency on data training because the social proÔ¨Åle provides personal information for accurate spam detection. In contrast, Bayesian completely relies on data training and needs a signiÔ¨Åcant amount of time to learn a new spam keyword. More training samples help to enhance its accuracy.
C. Training Time
We further compare the training time needed for SOAP and Bayesian to achieve the same accuracy. We deÔ¨Åne a training cycle as the time period of training that enables a node to learn a new type of spam. Figure 6 shows the accuracy rate versus the number of training cycles. We observe that the accuracy of both SOAP and Bayesian increases as the training cycle increases. Unlike SOAP which exhibits slight increase because its accuracy is already very high, the accuracy of Bayesian grows rapidly. Moreover, Bayesian needs about 60 cycles to learn a certain category of keywords to reach the same accuracy rate as SOAP, while SOAP already achieves high accuracy with one training cycle. This is because the social interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering component infers the (dis)interests of users from their on-line social proÔ¨Åles. Instead of letting user manually train the Bayesian Ô¨Ålter to detect the spam, SOAP can detect spam without learning based on social networks. Thus, SOAP does not need as much training time to achieve high spam detection accuracy rate.
D. Resilience to Impersonation Attacks
In this experiment, we consider the impersonation attack in which a spammer impersonates the identities of the benign

senders by forging their IDs or compromising their computers. We used a completely trained Bayesian with 6000 sample size to test how fast SOAP can adjust trust values to Ô¨Ålter the spam from an impersonated node. To mimic the behavior of impersonation attacks, we randomly selected 4 random nodes to continuously send 10 spam emails to 4 nodes whose closeness values are > 2. The simulation Ô¨Ånishes after 250 pair of nodes are selected. Recall that in SOAP, a node decreases another node‚Äôs trust value if it receives spam from that node.
Figure 7 shows the average accuracy rate versus the average number of spam emails between the selected pairs. The Ô¨Ågure shows that initially when a receiver receives spam from a highly-trustworthy sender, the spam detection accuracy is low. This is because SOAP trusts emails from close persons initially, and its closeness-based Ô¨Åltering component reduces the weight of spam keywords in emails sent from close people. Once the receiver detects the spam, it immediately reduces the trust value of the sender and checks the emails from the sender more strictly. This process is demonstrated in the Ô¨Ågure. As more spam emails are received by the receivers, SOAP‚Äôs accuracy rate grows rapidly. For SOAP with a < 0.5, its spam Ô¨Åltering accuracy rate is higher than Bayesian after receiving only one spam email. This is because using AIMD for trust adjustment, the accuracy rate of SOAP increases exponentially. A small a leads to a high trust value decreasing rate. Because Bayesian has been already well-trained, its accuracy rate remains high. We notice that the accuracy rate of RE remains 0. RE always regards the email senders in the whitelist trustable. Therefore, if spammers impersonate the identities of the persons in the whitelist, their spam will be accepted by all in the impersonated persons‚Äô FOF network. As RE has no trust adjustment mechanism, the accuracy rate of RE is low.
In this experiment, in addition to legitimate emails, nodes randomly send spam emails to their close nodes. Bayesian is only trained with partial spam keywords. Figure 8 shows the accuracy rate versus the training cycle of Bayesian, SOAP and RE. The Ô¨Ågure shows that it takes 20 ‚àí 30 training cycles for SOAP to adjust the trust to an appropriate value that reaches the maximum spam detection performance. It also shows that Bayesian takes 50‚àí60 cycles to learn the new spam keywords. This result matches the observation in Figure 6 that Bayesian needs more training time without using a social network, while SOAP needs less cycles relying on a social network. The result veriÔ¨Åes the effectiveness of the adaptive trust management

1842

component in SOAP. RE exhibits poor performance with less than 20% accuracy rate. The reason is the same as in Figure 7.
E. Resilience to Poison Attacks
In this experiment, we test the performance of Bayesian and SOAP under poison attacks. In this attack, extra legitimate keywords are added into spam to avoid to be detected. Figure 9 shows the decreased accuracy versus the number of legitimate keywords. As expected, the accuracy of both SOAP and Bayesian decreases. The detection accuracy of Bayesian decreases much faster than SOAP. This is because SOAP‚Äôs interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering component only focuses on the receivers‚Äô (dis)interest keywords in the emails regardless of other legitimate keywords. Because a spam is always sent out by Ô¨Çooding, it is unlikely for a spammer to search the interests of an individual receiver to poison his/her spam Ô¨Ålter. SOAP‚Äôs personalized feature enables it to avoid poison attacks to a certain degree. In contrast, Bayesian is not personalized and is vulnerable to poison attacks. Some emails do not contain the (dis)interest keywords of the receiver. In this case, SOAP resorts to its basic Bayesian function for spam detection. Thus, its detection accuracy also decreases. Since RE is an identitybased spam Ô¨Ålter, its accuracy is not affected by the content of an email. Thus, its performance does not change as more legitimate keywords are added into spam emails.
V. CONCLUSION
A personalized, attack-resilient and user-friendly spam Ô¨Ålter is needed to effectively combat spammers in order to reduce spam emails. However, most of current spam Ô¨Ålters cannot meet these requirements. Some Ô¨Ålters are vulnerable to spam Ô¨Ålter attacks and some are not user-friendly. Few spam Ô¨Ålters rely on social network to achieve personalized spam Ô¨Åltering to increase spam detection accuracy. In this paper, a SOcial network Aided Personalized and effective spam Ô¨Ålter (SOAP) is proposed to meet the requirements. SOAP offers three new components to be integrated into the Bayesian Ô¨Ålter. The social closeness-based spam Ô¨Åltering component prevents spam poison attacks, the social interest-based spam Ô¨Åltering component helps to realize personalized spam Ô¨Åltering, and the adaptive trust management component prevents impersonation attacks. More accurate spam Ô¨Åltering results function as input for Bayesian automatic training, leading to less need of user‚Äôs effort to distinguish spam emails. The results of trace driven experiments show that SOAP improves the performance of Bayesian networks in term of spam detection accuracy and training time. In the future, we plan to build a real testbed for testing the performance of SOAP with real interaction samples.
